h3. Problem Definition
Starting Confluence 6.5, Confluence does not support database privileges through roles. The DBA has to assign the following roles to the user directly otherwise *Confluence will not start.*

Our documentation [Database Setup for Oracle|https://confluence.atlassian.com/conf65/database-setup-for-oracle-939701687.html] mentions the following privileges need to be granted:
{code}
grant connect to <user>;
grant resource to <user>;
grant create table to <user>;
grant create sequence to <user>;
grant create trigger to <user>;
{code}

Based on Oracle's documentation: [Configuring Privilege and Role Authorization|https://docs.oracle.com/database/121/DBSEG/authorization.htm#DBSEG4414], the {{RESOURCE}} role already contains the following privileges: 
{quote}
Provides the following system privileges: CREATE CLUSTER, CREATE INDEXTYPE, CREATE OPERATOR, CREATE PROCEDURE, CREATE SEQUENCE, CREATE TABLE, CREATE TRIGGER, CREATE TYPE.
{quote}
(!) The DBA can choose *not* to include those in the {{RESOURCE}} role. 

Even when those privileges are granted through the {{RESOURCE}} role (default behavior), Confluence still expects those to be granted separately.


h3. Suggested Solution
Modify the database checks to verify:
# If the required privileges (one or more) are granted through the {{RESOURCE}} role, then continue with startup
# If they are not, check whether they are passed through a different role
# If they are not, check whether they are passed separately
# If they are not, Confluence should not start


h3. Workaround
The only available workaround is to grant those privileges directly to the database user

